<section class="seo-content">
  <div class="page-container seo-inner">
    <header class="seo-header">
      <span class="t-caption-mono eyebrow">About the tool</span>
      <h2 class="t-display-lg">The most private image converter on the web.</h2>
    </header>

    <div class="seo-body">
      <p class="t-body-md">
        <strong>PixelMorph</strong> is a free <strong>image converter</strong> that runs entirely inside your browser. Unlike every other "free online image converter" that uploads your files to a server, decodes them in a cloud function, and emails you a link, this tool does all of the work locally. Your photos, screenshots, scans, and design exports never leave your laptop or phone — there is no upload step, no queue, no waiting room, and no "we couldn't process your file" page.
      </p>

      <h3 class="t-display-sm">Convert between PNG, JPG, WebP, GIF, SVG, ICO and TIFF</h3>
      <p class="t-body-md">
        The converter supports the seven formats that cover roughly 95% of everyday image work:
      </p>
      <ul class="seo-list">
        <li><strong>PNG</strong> — the lossless default for screenshots, UI exports, and graphics with transparency.</li>
        <li><strong>JPG / JPEG</strong> — the photographic workhorse, lossy but tiny, supported everywhere.</li>
        <li><strong>WebP</strong> — Google's modern format, roughly 30% smaller than JPG at the same visual quality.</li>
        <li><strong>GIF</strong> — still the path of least resistance for short, embed-friendly animations.</li>
        <li><strong>SVG</strong> — vector container for icons, logos, and infinitely scalable artwork.</li>
        <li><strong>ICO</strong> — the canonical Windows favicon format, with multi-size support baked in.</li>
        <li><strong>TIFF</strong> — the print and archival standard, used by scanners and prepress pipelines.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="t-body-md">
        Every pair — 42 conversion directions in total — has its own dedicated landing page with format-specific guidance. Need to convert <a href="/png-to-jpg">PNG to JPG</a>, <a href="/jpg-to-webp">JPG to WebP</a>, <a href="/webp-to-png">WebP to PNG</a>, <a href="/svg-to-png">SVG to PNG</a>, <a href="/png-to-ico">PNG to ICO</a>, or <a href="/tiff-to-jpg">TIFF to JPG</a>? Just drop a file at the top of the page and pick a target format.
      </p>

      <h3 class="t-display-sm">Why a browser-only image converter matters</h3>
      <p class="t-body-md">
        Most free image converters online today route your images through a third-party server. That means your private photo, NDA-bound design comp, or medical scan is being uploaded, stored in a queue, processed on shared infrastructure, and (theoretically) deleted afterward. The "we promise we delete it" line has not aged well — it appears in the privacy policies of services that have later been breached, sold, or quietly trained AI models on user uploads.
      </p>
      <p class="t-body-md">
        Doing the conversion in the browser sidesteps the entire problem. Modern browsers can decode and encode PNG, JPG, WebP, and GIF natively using the Canvas API. We layer small, well-audited JavaScript libraries on top to handle the long tail (TIFF, ICO). The result is a free image converter that:
      </p>
      <ul class="seo-list">
        <li><strong>Doesn't upload anything.</strong> Open DevTools, switch to the Network tab, and watch — no requests carry your image bytes anywhere.</li>
        <li><strong>Has no file-size limit.</strong> The practical ceiling is your device's available memory; modern laptops handle 100MB+ images comfortably.</li>
        <li><strong>Has no daily quota.</strong> Convert one image or ten thousand — the tool doesn't know or care.</li>
        <li><strong>Has no signup wall.</strong> No email collection, no "verify to download," no paid tier hiding the obvious features.</li>
        <li><strong>Works offline.</strong> Once the page is loaded, the converter keeps working without an internet connection.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3 class="t-display-sm">Bulk image conversion, resize and quality control</h3>
      <p class="t-body-md">
        Beyond simple format-swapping, PixelMorph handles batch conversion (drop a folder, convert the lot, download as a single ZIP), quality tuning for lossy formats, automatic resize by percent or by maximum dimension, background-color flattening for transparency removal, and EXIF metadata stripping for privacy-sensitive uploads.
      </p>
      <p class="t-body-md">
        Common use cases include optimizing hero images for fast-loading websites (PNG&nbsp;→&nbsp;WebP), preparing batches of photos for print pipelines (JPG&nbsp;→&nbsp;TIFF), generating favicons for new web projects (PNG&nbsp;→&nbsp;ICO), converting Apple's HEIC photos to JPG for cross-platform sharing, and exporting vector icons to raster PNG for legacy CMS systems that don't accept SVG uploads.
      </p>

      <h3 class="t-display-sm">One tool, every common image converter job</h3>
      <p class="t-body-md">
        Whether you need a dedicated <strong>PNG converter</strong>, a <strong>JPEG converter</strong> for batch photo work, an <strong>SVG converter</strong> for vector exports, or a general <strong>vector image converter</strong> that rasterises SVG artwork to crisp PNG — every flow lives on this one page. The same goes for direction-specific jobs: <strong>image to JPG</strong>, <strong>image to WebP</strong>, <strong>image to PNG</strong>. Pick the source, pick the target, drop the file.
      </p>
      <p class="t-body-md">
        Because the encoder runs against your browser's full memory, PixelMorph is also a genuine <strong>high-resolution image converter</strong> — 4K, 5K, 8K, and panoramic exports are processed at full resolution with no automatic downsampling, no "free tier" watermark, and no "upgrade to convert files over 10&nbsp;MB" wall. If your laptop can open the file, this <strong>web image converter</strong> can convert it.
      </p>

      <p class="t-body-md">
        If you've previously used a clunky desktop converter — or worse, a sketchy ad-laden web tool — give the browser-based approach a try. It's faster, more private, and entirely free. Drop a file at the top of this page to get started, or browse the format pages below to learn which target format fits your specific need.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
